ef’s Narcissistic Sociality -- t10: The Postdramatic Paradox: Theater as an Interventionist Medium in Falk Richter’s Das System -- tPart V: Beyond Germany’s Borders: Social-Justice Issues in a Global Context -- t11: Settling in Mobility: Socioeconomic Justice and European Borderlands in Hans-Christian Schmid’s Films Lichter and Die wundersame Welt der Waschkraft -- t12: The Ethics of Listening in Dana Ranga’s Wasserbuch and Terézia Mora’s Das Ungeheuer -- t13: Navid Kermani: Advocate for an Antipatriotic Patriotism and a Multireligious, Multicultural Europe -- tNotes on the Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aExplores how contemporary German-language literary, dramatic, filmic, musical, and street artists are grappling in their works with social-justice issues that affect Germany and the wider world.Social-injustice dilemmas such as poverty, unemployment, and racism are subjects of continuing debate in European societies and in Germany in particular, as solutions are difficult and progress often comes slowly. Such discussionsare not limited to opposing newspaper editorials, position papers, or legislative forums, however; creative works expound on these topics as well, but their contributions to the debate are often marginalized. This collectionof new essays explores how contemporary German-language literary, dramatic, filmic, musical, and street artists are grappling with social-justice issues that affect Germany and the wider world, surveying more than a decade's worth of works of German literature and art in light of the recent paradigm shift in cultural criticism called the "ethical turn." Central themes include the legacy of the politically engaged 1968 generation, eastern Germany and the process of unification, widening economic disparity as a result of political policies and recession, and problems of integration and inclusivity for ethnic and religious minorities as migration to Germany has increased.Contributors: Monika Albrecht, Olaf Berwald, Robert Blankenship, Laurel Cohen-Pfister, Jack Davis, Bastian Heinsohn, Axel Hildebrandt, Deborah Janson, Karolin Machtans, Ralf Remshardt, Alexandra Simon-López, Patricia Anne Simpson,Maria Stehle, Jill E. Twark. Jill E. Twark is Associate Professor of German at East Carolina University. Axel Hildebrandt is Associate Professor of German at Moravian College.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aGerman literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aSocial justice in art. 0aSocial justice in literature. 4aFilm & Theatre. 4aGerman Literature. 4aModern History. 4aPolitics & Economics. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / German.2bisacsh  aAfrican democracy.  aContemporary Germany.  aEnvisioning Social Justice in Contemporary German Culture.  aNigerian politics.  aethnic and religious minorities.  amigration to Germany.  apolitical policies.  apoverty.  aracism.  arecession.  aunemployment.1 aAlbrecht, Monika, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerwald, Olaf, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlankenship, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCohen-Pfister, Laurel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavis, Jack, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHeinsohn, Bastian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHildebrandt, Axel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHildebrandt, Axel, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aJanson, Deborah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLópez, Alexandra Simon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.